recalls.Summary: Subaru of America, Inc. (Subaru) is recalling certain 2017-2018 Impreza and 2018 Crosstrek vehicles equipped with an aluminum Positive Crankcase Ventilation (PCV) valve.  The PCV valve may come apart, allowing the separated components to enter the engine, possibly resulting in a loss of power while driving.
recalls.Consequence: An unexpected loss of power while driving can increase the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Subaru will notify owners, and dealers will inspect and, if necessary, replace the PCV valve, free of charge.  If the PCV valve has separated and the components cannot be found, the engine will be replaced, free of charge.  The recall began December 2, 2019.  Owners may contact Subaru customer service at 1-844-373-6614.  Subaru's number for this recall is WUP-01.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Subaru of America, Inc. (Subaru) is recalling certain 2018-2019 Subaru Crosstrek, 2019 Crosstrek Hybrid, and 2019 Forester vehicles.  The rear stabilizer bracket bolts may loosen and detach.
recalls.Consequence: Missing bolts may allow the rear stabilizer bracket to shift, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Subaru will notify owners, and dealers will retorque and replace any missing bolts, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed May 17, 2021.  Owners may contact Subaru customer service at 1-844-373-6614.  Subaru's number for this recall is WRD-21.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Subaru of America, Inc. (Subaru) is recalling certain 2017-2019 Subaru Impreza and 2018-2019 Crosstrek vehicles.  The Engine Control Module (ECM) may continue to power the ignition coil after the engine is shut off, causing a short circuit.
recalls.Consequence: A short circuit in the ignition coils may cause a stall, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Subaru will notify owners, and dealers will update the ECM software, replace the ignition coils and, if necessary, the front exhaust pipe, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed beginning June 1, 2021.  Owners can contact Subaru customer service at 1-844-373-6614.  Subaru's number for this recall is WRE-21.  Note: This recall includes all vehicles previously repaired under Recall 19V743.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Subaru of America, Inc. (Subaru) is recalling certain 2017-2019 Impreza and 2018-2019 Crosstrek vehicles.  The Engine Control Module (ECM) may continue to power the ignition coil after the engine is shut off, which could result in a short circuit and blown fuse.
recalls.Consequence: If a short circuit occurs while driving, the vehicle may stall, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Subaru will notify owners, and dealers will update the ECM software and inspect and replace the ignition coil, as necessary, free of charge.  In addition, on vehicles with confirmed ignition coil damage and a certain stored diagnostic trouble code (DTC), Subaru will replace the front exhaust pipe, free of charge.  The recall began December 4, 2019.  Owners may contact Subaru customer service at 1-844-373-6614.  Subaru's number for this recall is WUQ-02.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Subaru of America, Inc. (Subaru) is recalling certain 2018 Crosstrek vehicles.  These vehicles may be equipped with an incorrect floor mat retention bracket, allowing the floor mat to move out of position and interfere with the accelerator or brake pedal operation.
recalls.Consequence: If the floor mat moves out of position and interferes with the accelerator or brake pedal operation, it can increase the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Subaru has notified owners, and dealers will inspect the floor mat retention bracket and replace it if necessary, free of charge.  The recall began November 14, 2017.  Owners may contact Subaru customer service at 1-800-782-2783.  Subaru's number for this recall is WTR-77.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

I am writing to formally raise a significant safety concern regarding my 2018 Subaru Crosstrek. I recently discovered a malfunction in the transfer case (pictures attached), specifically involving the center differential gear set, which necessitated immediate replacement. This issue first became apparent while driving at low speeds when I heard a loud, distinctive "clunking" noise, indicating a possible malfunction within the transmission. As a precaution, I took the vehicle to my service mechanic for further diagnosis.  After thorough inspection, my mechanic at Roberts Auto Shop (invoice attached) promptly identified the transfer case as the source of the problem. Subsequently, I contacted my local Subaru dealership, North Tampa, where I have previously serviced my vehicle, to inquire whether this issue is known to affect earlier models of the Crosstrek. The service manager expressed surprise that this problem occurred in my manual transmission vehicle, noting that it is typically documented in vehicles with CVT transmissions but rarely in manual models. I further inquired about the availability of any extended warranties or safety recalls related to this known issue. The manager informed me that the vehicle's powertrain warranty covers only up to 60,000 miles or five years, both of which I have exceeded, as my vehicle currently has just over 70,000 miles.  My primary safety concern arises from the discovery of metal shavings inside the defective transfer case during its replacement. While the amount is currently minimal, there is a significant risk that this could quickly escalate into a complete transmission failure, posing a considerable safety hazard.  I am planning to report this issue to Subaru of America for further investigation and would appreciate your assistance in investigating this matter. I also request that Subaru be held accountable for this known defect, particularly given its potential to jeopardize vehicle safety.  Thank you for your support.

THERE IS A NOTABLE DIFFERENCE IN THE SOUND MADE BY THE DRIVER LOCK.    THE CORRECTIVE ACTION IS TO USE THE EMERGENCY KEY CONTAINED IN THE KEYFOB AND TURN THE LOCK. FIRST, I BELIEVE SUBARY SHOULD NOTIFY CUSTOMERS OF THIS CONDITION, OF THE SIGNS IT EXISTS AND HOW TO RESOLVE IT. THE RISK IS REAL AND THEY SHOULD BE STATED.    SECOND, I BELIEVE THE SOLENOID THAT LOCKS THE DOOR IS TOO WEAK TO FREE ITSELF, AND SUBARU SHOULD UPGRADE THIS PART SO THAT IF THIS OCCURS, THE NEXT USE OF THE LOCK CORRECTS IT. issues.title: CVT Transmission Hesitation and Shuddering
issues.description: The Continuously Variable Transmission (CVT) exhibits hesitation, shuddering, or jerking during acceleration, particularly when merging onto highways or climbing hills. This is often accompanied by a whining noise and can affect drivability significantly.
issues.fix_description: CVT fluid change, software updates, or complete CVT replacement in severe cases. Some cases resolved with CVT fluid flush and filter replacement.
issues.prevention: Regular CVT fluid changes every 60,000 miles, avoid aggressive acceleration, warm up vehicle before driving in cold weather

issues.title: Excessive Oil Consumption
issues.description: The FB20 2.0L engine consumes excessive amounts of oil, sometimes requiring oil additions between scheduled changes. This can lead to engine damage if not monitored closely.
symptoms: Need to add oil between changes
issues.fix_description: Engine rebuild or replacement, piston ring replacement, or valve seal replacement depending on root cause. Some covered under extended warranty.
issues.prevention: Check oil level monthly, use recommended oil grade, avoid extended oil change intervals, monitor for early symptoms

issues.title: Windshield Cracking
issues.description: Windshields are prone to cracking from minor road debris or temperature changes. The glass appears to be thinner or more susceptible to damage than other vehicles.
issues.fix_description: Complete windshield replacement with OEM or aftermarket glass. Some insurance companies cover replacement.
issues.prevention: Maintain safe following distance, avoid extreme temperature changes, repair chips immediately, consider protective film

issues.title: Infotainment System Freezing and Connectivity Issues
issues.description: The STARLINK infotainment system experiences frequent freezing, slow response times, and connectivity problems with smartphones. Screen may go black or become unresponsive.
issues.fix_description: Software updates from dealer, factory reset of system, or replacement of infotainment unit in severe cases.
issues.prevention: Keep system software updated, avoid using multiple apps simultaneously, restart system periodically

issues.title: Premature Brake Pad and Rotor Wear
issues.description: Front brake pads and rotors wear prematurely, often requiring replacement before 30,000 miles under normal driving conditions.
issues.fix_description: Replace brake pads and rotors with higher quality aftermarket parts or genuine Subaru components.
issues.prevention: Avoid hard braking, use engine braking when possible, regular brake inspections, quality brake fluid changes

issues.title: Air Conditioning Compressor Failure
issues.description: The A/C compressor fails prematurely, resulting in no cold air production. Often occurs suddenly and may be accompanied by unusual noises from the engine bay.
issues.fix_description: Replace A/C compressor, receiver drier, and expansion valve. System flush and recharge with refrigerant.
issues.prevention: Run A/C system monthly year-round, replace cabin air filter regularly, address refrigerant leaks promptly

issues.title: Rear Hatch Strut Failure
issues.description: The rear hatch struts fail to hold the hatch open, causing it to fall or requiring manual support. This is a common wear item that fails earlier than expected.
issues.fix_description: Replace both rear hatch struts with new units. Should be done in pairs to maintain even support.
issues.prevention: Avoid forcing hatch open in freezing weather, don't overload hatch with heavy items, support hatch manually when showing signs of weakness

issues.title: Head Unit SD Card Failure
issues.description: The internal SD card in the infotainment system fails, causing navigation and system features to malfunction or become unavailable.
issues.fix_description: Replace internal SD card or update/reload system software at dealership.
issues.prevention: Avoid extreme temperatures, keep system updated, avoid force-shutting the infotainment system

issues.title: Engine Mount Failure
issues.description: Engine mounts, particularly the front engine mount, fail prematurely causing excessive engine vibration and noise transmission into the cabin.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed engine mount(s) with genuine Subaru parts or upgraded aftermarket mounts.
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive acceleration from stops, warm up engine before driving, regular inspection during maintenance

issues.title: Fuel Pump Failure
issues.description: The fuel pump fails suddenly, causing the engine to stall or not start. This can leave drivers stranded and typically occurs without warning.
issues.fix_description: Replace fuel pump assembly. May be covered under recall or extended warranty for certain VINs.
issues.prevention: Keep fuel tank above quarter full, use quality fuel, replace fuel filter as scheduled, avoid running on empty

issues.title: Subframe Corrosion
issues.description: Rear subframe experiences premature corrosion, particularly in salt-treated road areas, leading to structural weakness and potential safety concerns.
issues.fix_description: Subframe replacement or professional rust treatment and reinforcement. Some cases covered under extended warranty.
issues.prevention: Regular undercarriage washing, especially in winter, rust prevention treatment, avoid driving through deep salt water

issues.title: Faulty Door Handles
issues.description: Exterior door handles break or become difficult to operate, particularly in cold weather. The plastic components are prone to cracking.
symptoms: Door handle won't return to position
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty door handle assembly. Often covered under warranty if failure occurs early.
issues.prevention: Gentle operation in cold weather, avoid yanking on handles, keep handles clean and lubricated

editorial.tagline: Adventure-ready crossover with genuine Subaru soul
editorial.hero_blurb: The Crosstrek proves that practicality doesn't have to be boring. With standard all-wheel drive, respectable ground clearance, and that distinctive boxer rumble, it's the thinking person's entry into Subaru ownership.
editorial.essence: The Crosstrek is Subaru's most accessible adventure companion, offering genuine off-road capability wrapped in a practical, efficient package. It's not trying to be a sports car—it's focused on being your reliable partner for whatever life throws at you.
editorial.heritage: Born from the Impreza platform in 2012, the Crosstrek filled the gap between traditional sedans and larger SUVs. It carries forward Subaru's rally-bred DNA while prioritizing versatility and outdoor capability over outright performance.
editorial.design_philosophy: Function over flash defines the Crosstrek's approach. Designers prioritized visibility, cargo space, and rugged capability while maintaining an approachable size for daily driving and urban parking.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not a motorsport icon itself, the Crosstrek shares its foundation with rally-proven Impreza platforms and benefits from decades of Subaru's all-wheel drive development in competition.
editorial.engine_character: The naturally aspirated boxer engines deliver linear, predictable power with that signature Subaru thrum. The 2.0L feels adequately energetic around town, while the 2.5L provides noticeably more grunt for highway merging and loaded adventures.
editorial.transmission_feel: The CVT prioritizes efficiency over engagement, though it's well-tuned for the Crosstrek's mission. Manual mode provides some control, but this isn't about sporty shifting—it's about smooth, reliable power delivery.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Tuned for stability and comfort rather than corner carving. The suspension soaks up road imperfections admirably while providing enough articulation for light trail duty. Body roll is well-controlled for its height.
editorial.steering_feel: Light and easy around town with adequate feedback for confident highway cruising. It's not particularly communicative, but it's precise enough and perfectly suited to the Crosstrek's mission as a daily driver.
editorial.brake_confidence: Predictable and progressive braking with good pedal feel. The brakes inspire confidence in both city traffic and mountain descents, though they're tuned more for reliability than sport driving.
editorial.sound_signature: The classic Subaru boxer rumble is present but muted—distinctive enough for enthusiasts to recognize but refined enough for everyday comfort. Wind and road noise are well-controlled at highway speeds.
editorial.ideal_owner: Active individuals or families who need daily practicality with weekend adventure capability. Perfect for those who want Subaru reliability and all-wheel drive without stepping up to a larger, more expensive SUV.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Speed demons seeking sports car thrills or those needing heavy towing capacity. The CVT and modest power output won't satisfy performance enthusiasts or serious off-roaders.
editorial.buyers_summary: Focus on 2021+ models for the improved 2.5L engine if budget allows—the extra torque makes a meaningful difference. The Crosstrek's strength lies in its versatility and Subaru's legendary reliability, not raw performance.
best_for: Urban commuting with outdoor weekend adventures
Light off-road exploration and camping trips
